        <tr class='athing comtr ' id='14335905'><td>
            <table border='0'>  <tr>    <td class='ind'><img src="s.gif" height="1" width="80"></td><td valign="top" class="votelinks"><center><a id='up_14335905' href='vote?id=14335905&amp;how=up&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D14335310'><div class='votearrow' title='upvote'></div></a></center></td><td class="default"><div style="margin-top:2px; margin-bottom:-10px;"><span class="comhead">
          <a href="user?id=oren_thrall" class="hnuser">oren_thrall</a> <span class="age"><a href="item?id=14335905">5 hours ago</a></span> <span id="unv_14335905"></span><span class="par"></span> <a class="togg" n="12" href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="return toggle(event, 14335905)"></a>          <span class='storyon'></span>
                  </span></div><br><div class="comment">
                  <span class="c00">I generally get the feeling that people were way more wreckless before the 80&#x27;s. The level of technology at the time is surprisingly low. Card catalogs and the dewey decimal system represented a nominal level of information technology, rendering many audit trails nearly opaque.<p>Of course, physical, structural security was bad too. Break a window and climb on in, just repair the window when you leave and maybe that&#x27;d be enough to capture some records. If it wasn&#x27;t a bank or a prison, a building probably wasn&#x27;t a fortress unless it was extra special.<p>People cared a lot less about how life turned out 40 or 50 years ago. Alcohol, tobacco, diseases everywhere, and medicine was kind of terrible. You get a feel that risk taking was normal.<p>Now, people clench up at the thought of breaking any rules. Call it the new technological superstition. We don&#x27;t believe in god, but we believe in logs.<span>
              </span><div class='reply'>        <p><font size="1">
                      <u><a href="reply?id=14335905&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D14335310%2314335905">reply</a></u>
                  </font>
      </div></td></tr>
